<subSubSection pageId="226" pageNumber="831" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="226.[1373,2579,2302,3005]" pageId="226" pageNumber="831">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1375,1730,2735,2769]" pageId="226" pageNumber="831">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Endangered on The IUCN Red List. Estimated extent of occurrence of the Nicobar Archipelago Rat is only 2841 km*. There is almost nothing known about its natural history, taxonomy, or conservation threats, although a tsunami in 2004 seems to have been 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hatt" authorityYear="1934" box="[1886,1992,2858,2887]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Thamnomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="226" pageNumber="848" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="major">a major</taxonomicName>
threat, prompting human expansion and habitat destruction; its population is apparently decreasing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
